Sometimes I feel ashamed of being a European.
Last year, more than a million people in need of our help arrived in Europe and our response was frankly pathetic.
There are so many contradictions.
We mourn the tragic death of Alan Kurdi, a two-year-old child, and yet, since then, more than 200 children have drowned in the Mediterranean.
International treaties recognise that refugees are a collective responsibility, and yet we accept that little Lebanon should welcome more Syrians than the whole of the united Europe.
We are lamenting the existence of smugglers, yet we are making the only viable path to seek asylum in Europe.
We lack the workforce, yet we are preventing people who meet our economic and demographic needs from coming to Europe.
We proclaim our liberal values in opposition to fundamentalist Islam, yet -- we have repressive policies that arrest minor asylum seekers, that separate children from their families and that seize the property of refugees.
What are we doing?
How did we get there, so we adopted such an inhumane response to a humanitarian crisis?
I do not believe that this is due to a lack of interest, at least I do not want to believe it.
I believe that it is because our politicians have no vision, that they do not know how to adapt the international asylum rules, created more than 50 years ago, to globalisation.
I want to take a step back and ask two fundamental questions, the two questions that we all have to ask.
Firstly, why does the current system not work?
Secondly, how can we remedy it?
The current regime for refugees was created following the consequences of World War II by these people.
Its primary purpose is to ensure that when a State fails, or worse, turns against its people, people have a place to go, where to live in safety and dignity until they can return.
It was created precisely for situations such as the current situation in Syria.
Through an international convention signed by 147 Governments, the 1951 Convention relating to the Status of Refugees, and an international organization, UNHCR, States have undertaken to admit reciprocally persons fleeing conflict and persecution to their territory.
But today, this system is failing.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek asylum.
In practice, our immigration policies are blocking the path to security.
In theory, refugees have the right to integration or return to their countries of origin.
But in practice, they get stuck in eternal limbo.
In theory, refugees are a common global responsibility.
In practice, geography means that countries close to the conflict host the overwhelming majority of refugees.
The system is not broken because the rules are bad
But because we are not applying them properly to a changing world, and that is what we need to reconsider.
I'm going to explain to you how the current system works.
How did the current refugee regime work?
But not from an institutional perspective, rather from the point of view of a refugee.
Imagine a Syrian woman. Let's call her Amira.
To me, Amira represents
A lot of people I've met in the area.
Amira, like 25 percent of the world's refugees, is a woman with children, and she can't go home because she comes from this city that you see: Homs. A city that was beautiful and historic and is now in ruins.
Amira can't go back.
But Amira has no hope of settling in a third country, because there is a lottery available to just less than 1% of the refugees.
Amira and her family face an impossible choice.
They have three options.
The first option is that Amira takes her family to a camp.
In the camp, she could be helped, but there is little future for Amira and her family.
The camps are in austere and arid places, often in the desert.
In Jordan's camp, at night, you hear the bombings across the border.
Economic activity is restricted.
Education is often of poor quality.
Worldwide, about 80 per cent of refugees in camps must remain there for at least five years.
It's a miserable life, and that's probably why, in reality, only 9% of Syrians choose this option.
An alternative for Amira is to head to the urban area of a neighbouring country, such as Amman or Beirut.
It is an option chosen by about 75% of Syrian refugees.
But it also involves difficulties.
Refugees in such urban areas often do not have the right to work.
They often do not have access to help.
And so when Amira and his family have spent all their savings, they will have nothing left and will be in urban poverty.
There is a third possibility that an increasing number of Syrians will choose.
Amira can seek hope for her family by risking their lives on a dangerous and perilous journey to another country, and that is what we see today in Europe.
We therefore offer refugees an almost impossible choice between three options: encampment, urban poverty or a dangerous journey.
For refugees, this choice is the refugee regime of today.
But I think it's a false choice.
We can reconsider that choice.
The reason we are limiting these options is because we believe that these are the only options available to refugees, but that is not the case.
Politicians see this as a zero-sum problem, if we benefit refugees, citizens pay the price.
We tend to think that refugees are an inevitable cost or a burden on society.
But they don't have to be. They can contribute.
What I want to say is that there are ways to increase opportunities and that everyone benefits: host countries and communities, our societies and refugees.
And I want to suggest four ways to transform our view of refugees.
These four points of view have one thing in common: they include the opportunities of globalization, mobility and markets, and modernize our way of thinking about the refugee problem.
The first idea is that of favourable environments. It begins with the fundamental recognition that refugees are human beings like everyone else, but with extraordinary circumstances.
Together with my colleagues in Oxford, we embarked on a research project in Uganda, observing the economic life of the refugees.
We have chosen Uganda, not because it is representative of all host countries.
It is exceptional.
Unlike the majority of host countries, Uganda had given refugees an economic opportunity.
It gives them the right to work, the freedom to move.
And the results are extraordinary for refugees and for the host community.
In the capital, Kampala, we have discovered that 21 per cent of refugees have a business that employs people and 40 per cent of these employees are natives of the host country.
In other words, refugees create work for the citizens of the host country.
Even in the camps, we have discovered extraordinary examples of dynamic and thriving companies.
For example, in a village called Nakivale, we have the example of Congolese refugees running digital music-sharing companies.
We found a Rwandan running a company to enable young people to play video games on recycled consoles and televisions.
Despite the difficulties of extreme constraints, refugees innovate and the man you see is a Congolese named Demoused.
Demou-Kay arrived in the encampment with very few properties, but he wanted to become a director.
So, with friends and colleagues, he started a community radio station, he rented a camera and made movies.
He made two documentaries with and for our team and he's starting a successful business with almost nothing.
It is such examples that should guide our response to refugees.
Rather than seeing refugees as inevitably dependent on humanitarian assistance, we must provide them with the opportunity for human development.
Yes, clothes, blankets, shelter, food are very important in the emergency phase, but we need to go further.
We must offer the opportunity for connectivity, electricity, education, the right to work, access to banks.
Everything we see for granted, that integrates us into the global economy can and should be offered to refugees.
The second idea I want to talk about is the economic zones.
Unfortunately, not all the host countries of the world have the approach of Uganda.
Most host countries do not open their economies to refugees in this way.
But there are always pragmatic options that we can use.
Last April, I went to Jordan with my colleague, the development economist, Paul Collier, and we reflected on an idea that we had there with the international community and the government, an idea to create jobs for Syrians while supporting Jordan's national development strategy.
This is the idea of an economic zone where we could potentially integrate the employment of refugees and the employment of the natives of the host country.
At 15 minutes from the camp, which houses 83,000 refugees, there is the development zone of King Hussein Bin Talal.
The government spent more than 100 million dollars connecting it to the electricity grid and road grid, but there were two things missing: access to labour and foreign investment.
so that refugees can work there rather than being stranded in camps, support their families, develop skills through vocational training before returning to Syria.
We recognized that Jordan would benefit, as its development strategy required a shift from a middle-income country to an industrial country.
Refugees would benefit from it, but it would also contribute to the post-war reconstruction of Syria, recognizing that we must incubate the refugees because they are the best resource for rebuilding Syria.
We published this idea in the journal Foreign Affairs.
King Abdullah took up the idea.
This was announced at the London conference on Syria and a test will begin in the summer.
The third idea I want to submit to you is the notion of preference between states and refugees leading to positive results that you see in this selfie where Angela Merkel and a Syrian refugee are.
We rarely ask refugees what they want, where they want to go, but we can do it and it will be better for everyone.
The economist Alvin Roth has developed the idea of market adequacy, where the order of preference of the parties determines their possible correspondence.
My colleagues Will Jones and Alex Teytelboym have looked at ways to apply this idea to refugees, to ask refugees to rank destinations but also to allow States to rank the type of refugees desired on the basis of competence or language, and then match them.
Of course, quotas should be introduced on diversity and vulnerability, but this is one way of increasing the chances of correspondence.
The idea of correspondence is used successfully to, for example, distribute students to university, match kidney donors and patients, and the algorithm exists at dating sites.
Why not apply this to offer choice to refugees?
It could also be used at the national level, where one of the greatest challenges is to persuade local communities to accept refugees.
Currently, in my country, for example, we often send engineers in rural areas and farmers to the city, which makes no sense.
The matching markets make it possible to combine these preferences and to listen to the needs and demands of the host population and the refugees.
The fourth idea I am referring to is the principle of a humanitarian visa.
Tragedies and disorders in Europe could have been avoided.
They come from a fundamental contradiction in European asylum policy: in order to apply for asylum in Europe, you must arrive spontaneously by embarking on a dangerous journey that I have already mentioned.
But why are these journeys necessary in the era of low-cost airlines and modern consular resources?
These journeys are not necessary and, last year, they led to the deaths of more than 3 000 people on the borders of Europe and on European territory.
If refugees had the right to travel directly and to apply for asylum in Europe, we would avoid that. And we can do that with humanitarian visas that allow people to obtain a visa from an embassy or consulate in a neighbouring country and then by paying for their ferry or air to Europe.
It costs around EUR 1 000 to pay a smuggler from Turkey to the Greek islands.
A low-cost flight from Bodrum to Frankfurt costs 200 euros.
If we allowed the refugees, that would have major benefits.
This would save lives, it would weaken the market for smugglers and mark the end of the disorder observed in the first European line in areas such as the Greek islands.
It is the laws that prevent us from doing so, not a rational solution.
This is an idea that has been applied.
Brazil had taken a forward-looking approach and more than 2,000 Syrians had obtained humanitarian visas, had gone to Brazil and, on arrival, applied for refugee status.
In this configuration, every Syrian who did this was granted refugee status and was recognized as a refugee.
There is a historic precedent.
Between 1922 and 1942, these Nansen passports were used as travel documents authorizing 450,000 Assyrians, Turks and Chechens to travel to Europe and apply for refugee status elsewhere in Europe.
And the Nansen International Refugee Bureau was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in recognition of this viable strategy.
Each of these four ideas that I've presented to you are ways to extend Admira's choices.
These are ways we can increase the choice of refugees beyond these options, these three impossible options that I have detailed to you, while benefiting others.
In conclusion, we need a new perspective that extends the choice of refugees but recognizes that they do not have to be a burden.
There is nothing inevitable about the fact that refugees are a cost.
Yes, they are a humanitarian responsibility, but they are human beings with skills, talents, aspirations and the ability to contribute, if we allow them to do so.
In the new world, migration will not stop.
What we have seen in Europe will continue for years.
People will still travel, people will be displaced and we need to find rational and realistic ways to manage it, not based on the old logic of humanitarian aid, charity, but built on the opportunities offered by globalisation, markets and mobility.
I urge you to wake you up and I urge our politicians to wake up to this challenge.
Thank you very much.
