When I moved to Harare in 1985, social justice was at the heart of the country's national health policy.
The new government was emerging from a long war of independence and immediately announced a socialist agenda: health services, primary education became essentially free.
A significant expansion of rural health centres has placed about 80 per cent of the population within a two-hour walk of one of these centres, a truly remarkable achievement.
In 1980, the year of independence, 25 per cent of the children in the country were fully immunized.
In 1990, a decade later, that proportion was 80 per cent.
I felt extremely privileged to be part of this transformation, a revolution.
The excitement, the comradeship, were palpable.
By working with brilliant people, scientists, doctors, activists -- I felt connected not only to an African independence movement, but to a progressive global public health movement.
But there were considerable challenges.
It reported its first case of AIDS in 1985, the year I arrived.
I had taken care of a few AIDS patients in the early 1980s, during my medical training at Harlem Hospital, but we had no idea what was waiting for Africa.
My first days there, the infection rate was 2%.
It was going to skyrocket and reach one adult in four by the time I left Harare, 17 years later.
In the mid-1990s, I had announced to hundreds of people in their life as their HIV.
I had seen friends and colleagues die, my students, patients in the hospital.
In response to that, my colleagues and I set up a clinic.
We were demonstrating the use of condoms.
We have launched school education, work-based interventions.
We were doing research. We were giving advice to the partners of infected men so that they could protect themselves.
We worked hard, and at the time, I thought I was doing my best.
I was providing an excellent treatment, as good as possible.
But I was not talking about structural change.
The former UN Secretary, Kofi Annan, spoke honestly about his personal failure that led to the Rwandan genocide.
In 1994, he was the Director of the Peace Department at the United Nations.
In a memorial 10 years later, he said, "At the time, I thought I was doing my best, but I realized after the genocide that I could and should have done more to sound the alarm and gather support. ”
The AIDS epidemic caught the health community by surprise, and today, when the World Health Organization estimates that 39 million people died as a result of this disease, I'm not alone in feeling remorse and regret that I didn't do more, earlier.
But when I lived in the country, I didn't see my role as a defender or a politician.
I was there because of my technical skills, my clinical skills and my epidemiological research.
For me, my job was to take care of patients and do research to better understand the patterns of transmission within the population, and I hoped that we would slow down the spread of the virus.
I was aware that marginal populations were very likely to have and die from AIDS.
And in sugar plantations, which closely looked more like feudal fiefdoms than any modern company, 60 percent of pregnant women had HIV.
I worked to show that being infected was not a moral failure but rather linked to a culture of male superiority, forced labour of immigrants and colonialism.
Whites were largely spared.
As health professionals, our tools were pitifully weak: imploring people to change their individual behavior, to use condoms, to reduce the number of partners.
Infection rates were rising. And when treatment was available in the West, treatment that remained our most powerful weapon against the virus, it was not affordable for the African public sector.
I have not denounced the unequal access to these life-saving medicines or the underlying economic and political systems that raised infection rates among large groups of the population.
I rationalized my silence by thinking that I was just a visitor to this country, that the alarm could make me expel, prevent me from doing my job, taking care of my patients, carrying out such necessary research.
So I didn't revolt against the government's initial position on AIDS.
I did not express my concerns out loud.
Many doctors and health professionals may think I haven't done anything wrong.
Our pact with our patients, the Hippocrates' oath and its variants, evokes the inviolability of the patient-doctor relationship.
I did everything I could for every patient I had.
But I knew that epidemics appear along the cracks of our society, reflecting not only our biology, but more significantly the patterns of marginalization, exclusion, discrimination related to race, gender, sexuality, class, etc.
That was true for AIDS.
This was true recently for Ebola.
Medical anthropologists like Paul Farmer, who worked on AIDS in Haiti, called it "structural violence." Structural because inequality is embedded in the political and economic organization of our social world, and are often invisible to people privileged and in power; and violence because its impact -- premature deaths, suffering, disease -- is violent.
We do little for our patients if we do not recognize these social injustices.
Sounding the alarm is the first step towards good public health practice, and that is how we could bring back the support to revolutionise and create change together.
Today, I don't stay silent.
I'm talking about a lot of things, even if they make them uncomfortable, even if they make me uncomfortable.
Much of what I say is related to racial differences and institutionalized racism, things that are no longer supposed to exist in this country, let alone in medical practice or public health.
But they exist and we pay them by shortening lives.
That is why heals the alarm about the impact of racism on health in the United States, the current institutional and interpersonal violence facing people of color, mixed with our sad legacy of 250 years of slavery, 90 years of Jim Crow and 60 years of imperfect equality, sounding the alarm about this is fundamental to the successful completion of my work as New York City Health Commissioner.
In New York, premature mortality - either die before it reaches the age of 65 - is 50% higher for black men than for white men.
In 2012, a black woman was 10 times more likely than a white woman to die giving birth.
Although we have made enormous strides in reducing infant mortality rates, a black baby is always nearly three times more likely than a white baby to die in its first year.
New York is no exception.
These statistics are compared with statistics made across the United States.
A recent analysis by The New York Times pointed out that there was, in the country,
1.5 million black men missing. They mentioned the fact that more than one in six black men who were now between the ages of 25 and 54 were no longer living a normal life, but was in prison or died prematurely.
There is a great injustice to the daily and disproportionate violence against young black men, which is being paid to the recent protests by BlackLivesMatter.
But we must remember that disparate rates that persist and the occurrence and outcome of common diseases – heart disease, cancer, diabetes, HIV – diseases that can kill gently and silently and take even more black lives prematurely.
When the 'BlackLivesMatter' movement took shape, I was frustrated and angry that the medical community was reluctant to use the word "racism" in our research and work.
You must have felt something every time I said it.
Our students participated in white gown demonstrations, but the majority of the medical community has stood aside while current discrimination continues to affect the pattern of disease and mortality.
And I'm afraid that the fashion of personalized and accurate medicine, the search for biological or genetic targets for a more appropriate treatment, could inadvertently make us lose sight of the global situation, that is, the everyday context, where a person lives, grows, works, loves, fundamental factor in determining the health of the population: for too many of us, poor health.
As health professionals, in our daily work, whether in practice or in research, we witness a great injustice: the homeless who are unable to follow medical advice because they have other priorities; transgender youth who think of suicide because our society is too rigid; the single mother who is being blamed for the poor health of her child.
Our role as healthcare professionals is not only to treat our patients but to sound the alarm and promote change.
Whether it is legally or not, our position in society makes us very credible and we should not spoil that.
I regret that I did not take the floor in the country, and I promised myself that, as New York City Health Commissioner, I would use every opportunity I would have to sound the alarm and get support for health equity.
I will denounce racism, and I hope you will join me, and I will join you in denouncing sexism or any other form of inequality.
It is time to stand up and, as a community, denounce structural inequalities.
We don't need to have all the answers to call for change.
We only need courage.
The health of our patients, of all of us, depends on it.
