This is the word “delayed” or “backward” used in a derogatory manner.
They can't imagine how much it hurts me and my friends.
I don't want you to think I'm here to be a work of charity.
I'm here because there's always a big problem with how many people perceive individuals with intellectual disabilities, or, all too often, how they don't see them at all.
Did you know that the World Championships took place this year?
I was among the more than 6,500 athletes with intellectual disabilities from 165 countries competing in Los Angeles.
There were over 62,000 spectators at the opening ceremonies, and there were TSN and ESPN to cover the event.
Did you know that this event took place?
What do you think when you meet someone like me?
I am here today to challenge you to regard us as equal.
The Special Olympics transform the identity of athletes with intellectual disabilities and the perception of anyone watching the competition.
For those of you who do not know, the Special Olympics are aimed at sportsmen and sportswomen with intellectual disabilities.
The Special Olympics are separated from the Paralympic and Olympic Games.
We offer high-quality sports programmes throughout the year for people with intellectual disabilities, which changes lives and perception.
This movement changed my life and so many other people.
And that has changed the way the world sees people with intellectual disabilities.
I was born with epilepsy and with an intellectual disability.
Growing up, I played hockey until I was 12.
The more I grew, the more I felt that it was harder to keep up with others, and I was pissed off and frustrated.
For a while, I didn't play any more sports, no longer had any friends, and felt forgotten and sad.
There was a time when people with intellectual disabilities were hidden from society.
No one thought they could practice a sport, let alone be an important member of society.
In the '60s, Dr. Frank Hayden, a scientist at the University of Toronto, studied the effects of regular exercise on the physical condition of children with intellectual disabilities.
Using rigorous scientific research, Dr. Hayden and other researchers concluded that it was simply the lack of opportunity to participate that led to physical fitness problems.
Many people doubted that people with intellectual disabilities could benefit from fitness programmes and sports competitions.
But pioneers like Dr. Hayden and Eunice Kennedy Shriver, the founder of the Special Olympics, persevered, and the athletes of the Special Olympics proved them four and a half million times.
Before I joined the Special Olympics, I was nervous because I was young, shy, and had little confidence in myself and I didn't have many friends.
When I arrived, yet everyone encouraged me a lot, endured me and let me be myself unjudged.
Now I'm a basketball player and speed skater who has competed in regional, national games, and this year ended up at the Summer World Games in Los Angeles, where I was part of the first Canadian basketball team to compete in the World Games.
I'm one of the more than four and a half million athletes from all over the world, and I've heard so many similar stories.
Being an athlete at the Special Olympics gives pride and dignity.
The Special Olympics also address significant health needs.
Studies have indicated that, on average, men with intellectual disabilities die 13 years younger than men without men, and women with intellectual disabilities die 20 years younger than women without them.
The Special Olympics keep us healthy by making us active and engaging in a sport.
In addition, our coaches teach us nutrition and health.
The Special Olympics also provide free screening tests for athletes who have difficulty communicating with their doctor or accessing medical care.
At the 2015 World Summer Games, my teammates Canada and I were playing against the Nigeria team.
