This change for them was unbelievable.
They were very excited, contented and confident, because their coaches could communicate orally with them.
And they were very moved because they could hear the sounds of the basketball, the whistle sounds and the enthusiastic fans in the stands -- sounds that we take for granted.
The Special Olympics do more than transform athletes into sport.
The Special Olympics are transforming their lives outside the field.
This year, research has shown that almost half of adults in the United States do not know a single person with an intellectual disability, and the 44% of Americans who do not have personal contact with intellectual disabilities are significantly less tolerant and positive.
Then there's the word "R," showing that people with intellectual disabilities are still invisible to far too many people.
People use it as a usual term or an insult.
He was tweeted more than nine million times last year, and it's deeply hurting me and my four and a half million athlete comrades around the world.
People don't think it's insulting, but it is.
As my fellow athlete and global spokesperson John Franklin Stephens wrote in an open letter to a political commentator who had used the word "R" as an insult, "Come one day join us at the Special Olympics.
You'll see if you go back with the heart unchanged. ”
