Jackie is a record holder among all Newfoundland weightlifters – not just at the Special Olympics, but all the weightlifters.
Jackie was a huge celebrity in Los Angeles, and ESPN tweeted live its new record and was impressed by its performance.
Fifty years ago, few people imagined people with mental disabilities who could do something like this.
This year, 60,000 spectators filled the famous LA Memorial Coliseum to watch the opening ceremonies of the World Games and applaud athletes from 165 countries from around the world.
Far from being hidden, we were applauded and celebrated.
The Special Olympics teach athletes to be confident and proud of themselves.
The Special Olympics teach the world that people with intellectual disabilities deserve respect and consideration.
Now I have dreams and successes in my sport, great coaches, respect and dignity, better health, and I'm pursuing a career as a personal trainer.
I'm no longer hidden, mocked, and I'm here giving a TED Talk.
The world is a different place thanks to the Special Olympics, but there is still work to be done.
So the next time you see someone with intellectual disabilities, I hope you'll see their talent.
Next time someone uses the word "R" next to you, I hope you'll tell them how hurtful it is.
