No doubt you don't know Kenema in Sierra Leone, or Arua in Nigeria.
For me these are the two most extraordinary places on Earth.
There, in hospitals, there is a community of nurses, doctors and scientists who have calmly fought against one of humanity's deadliest threats in years: the Lassa virus.
The Lassa virus resembles the Ebola virus.
It can cause a high fever and can often be fatal.
But these people risk their lives every day, to protect individuals in their communities, and ultimately protect us all.
One of the most extraordinary things I've learned about them, during one of my first visits, a long time ago, was that they start every morning -- those difficult mornings on the front lines -- singing.
They gather together, and they show their joy and strength.
Over the years, we have visited each other. I could be among them, sing, and write. It was extraordinary, because it reminds us that we are not only here for science, but that we are bound by shared humanity.
You can imagine, it's extremely important, even vital, when things started to change.
The situation changed in March 2014, when the Ebola outbreak was declared in Guinea.
It was the first epidemic in West Africa, near the border of Sierra Leone and Liberia.
It was scary... We were all terrified.
We had been suspecting for some time that the Lassa and Ebola viruses were more widespread than previously thought, that it could reach Kenema.
So members of my team immediately joined Dr. Humarr Khan and his team on the ground. We have put in place diagnostics to perform molecular tests that can detect the arrival of Ebola in Sierra Leone.
We had already managed to control the Lassa virus. We knew how to do it, the team was remarkable.
We just had to give them the tools and the lab for Ebola.
Unfortunately, that day has arrived.
On 23 May 2014, a woman arrived at the hospital's maternity ward. The team conducted molecular tests and identified the first case of Ebola in Sierra Leone.
It was an exceptional job.
They were able to diagnose the case immediately, treat the patient safely, and begin to understand what was going on.
It could have prevented what happened.
But the day it happened, the epidemic had been smouldering for several months.
There were already hundreds of cases, surpassing all previous outbreaks.
It entered Sierra Leone, not as this singular case, but as a tidal wave.
We have worked with the international community, the Ministry of Health, with Kenema, to deal with cases. The following week there were 31, and then 92 and then 147 cases, they all came to Kenema, one of the only places in Sierra Leone that could solve this problem.
We worked tirelessly, trying everything possible to help every person, and try to get attention. We also did something else:
We didn't throw away the blood tests, used to detect Ebola, we put them in a chemical to turn them off. We packed them and shipped them across the ocean.
We sent them to Boston, where my team is working.
We have also worked tirelessly, day in and day out. We quickly generated 99 Ebola genomes.
The genome is the architect's plan for a virus.
We all have one.
It indicates what we are made of, and it conveys so much information about us.
The results of this kind of work are simple and very useful.
We took these 99 different viruses, we observed and compared them, and we found that, by comparing them to the three genomes that had previously been published in Guinea, the epidemic had emerged in Guinea several months earlier, and that, once in humans, it was transmitted from human to human.
This is very important when it comes to determining how to intervene, because contact testing is very important.
It was also discovered that the virus mutated by moving between humans.
Every mutation is important because diagnoses, vaccines, and our therapies are all based on genome sequence. That's the guide.
Global health experts need to react, develop and re-calibrate all their work accordingly.
But science doesn't work that way. My position at the time was that I had the data and I could have worked in a silo for months, analyze the data carefully, slowly, submit an article for publication, make some changes, and finally publish my data after the official publication.
That is how the status quo in science works.
This time, there is no question of doing so.
We had friends on the ground. For us, it was obvious that we needed help, a lot of help ...
The first thing we did, as soon as the machine took out the first sequences, was to publish them on the web.
We have published them and called for help.
And the help came.
Soon, a lot of people contacted us, surprised by the data we had published.
Some of the world's greatest infectious scientists were part of our community.
We were working together in a virtual way, sharing regular calls, trying to track the virus minute by minute, to see how to stop it.
There are so many ways to form such communities.
Everyone, when the epidemic began to spread globally, wanted to learn, participate, and engage.
Everyone wanted to play a role.
The number of volunteers was incredible, and the Internet was connecting us all.
Can you imagine that instead of being afraid of each other, we would say, "OK, let's go, while working together,
We're going to defeat this virus. ”
The problem was that the data we used, by searching the web, was too limited for our purpose.
We spoil a lot of opportunities in these cases.
So when the epidemic broke out in Kenema, we had 106 patient clinical records, and we made them public.
In our lab, we demonstrated that, with these 106 folders, we could teach our computers to predict Ebola with an accuracy of about 100 percent.
We've developed an application that gives access to this information to on-site health workers.
Unfortunately, 106 cases are not sufficient to consolidate and validate the data.
So we were expecting more data.
But we were still waiting for the data.
We are still waiting, confined in our silos, instead of working together.
This situation is no longer tolerable.
You, all of you, can't accept that anymore.
It is our life that is at stake.
Many people have lost their lives, health workers, including colleagues who were dear to me. Five colleagues lost their lives: Mbalu Fonnie, Alex Moigboi, Dr. Humarr Khan, Alice Koroma and Mohamed Fullah.
These are just five of many others in Kenema and beyond, dead, as the world waited and we worked, quietly and separately.
Ebola, like all threats to humanity, is fuelled by mistrust, confusion and division.
As we build barriers between us, the virus develops.
Unlike all other threats, in the face of Ebola, we are all equal.
We're all on the same boat.
Ebola is on our every threshold.
And so in this place, we share the same vulnerabilities, forces, fears and hopes, I hope that we can work together with pleasure and pleasure.
One of my former students was reading a book about Sierra Leone, and she found out that the term "Kenema," the hospital where we work, in Sierra Leone, comes from Mende's quote for "clear as a river, translucent and open to glance."
It had a special meaning for us, because, unknowingly, we had always thought that to honor individuals in Kenema, we had to work openly and together.
We must do that.
We must all demand from ourselves and others, to be open to each other, when an epidemic occurs, and to fight it together.
Because it's not the first Ebola outbreak, nor the last, and there's a lot of other pathogens around us, like the Lassa virus.
The next epidemic could affect a city of millions of people.
It could start there and be transmitted by air.
It could even be intentionally disseminated.
I know it's scary, I understand ... but I also know, this experience proves it to us, that we have the technology and the ability to win, to win and get ahead of other viruses.
But this is only possible if we collaborate with joy.
For Dr. Khan, and for all those who have given their lives, on the front, in this fight with us, let us be at their side in this struggle. Always.
Let us not leave the world with the stigma of the destruction caused by a virus. Let's illuminate it with the brightness of billions of hearts and minds working in unity.
Thank you.
